[UTCTime "01:03:29"]

{ First rule of this ending - if you can successfully drop your queen in front of the pawn, you win automatically. You simply walk the king up and capture the pawn with support. }
1. Qf1! $18 { [%cal Bh8e3] } (1. Qg6+ Kh2 2. Qf5 Kg1 $10 { is a book draw, as the pawn is a bishop pawn. }) *


[Event "Queen vs. Rook or Bishop Pawns: Usual Winning Procedure"]
[Date "2018.01.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs. Rook or Bishop Pawns"]
[ChapterName "Usual Winning Procedure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kkoVo7Fy/CFHkEEbL"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/TonyRo"]
[FEN "7K/8/1Q6/8/8/8/3kp3/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.01.17"]
[UTCTime "00:19:31"]

{ Here White's queen cannot sit in front of the pawn, which has reached the seventh rank, one move away from promotion (and a likely draw). This is the simplest case, and the most important to learn up front. As long as White can start with a check, and the pawn is NOT a bishop or rook pawn (a, c, f, or h), it's a win. If the pawn is a bishop or rook pawn, more information is needed to evaluate whether or not Black can draw. } { [%csl Yb2,Yd2,Ye2,Yg2] }
1. Qd4+ Kc2 2. Qe3! Kd1 3. Qd3+! { This is the main idea - White repeatedly sets up a check that attacks the pawn at the same time, forcing the king to block the promotion square. This gives the White king a free move to start advancing towards the battle. White will repeat this sequence over and over again until the king is active enough to win the pawn. One possible winning line is: } { [%cal Bd1c1,Bd3e2] } 3... Ke1 { [%cal Re2e1] } 4. Kg7! Kf2 5. Qd2 (5. Qd4+ Kf1 6. Qf4+ Kg1 7. Qe3+ Kf1 8. Qf3+ { is the same idea. }) 5... Kf1 6. Qf4+ Kg2 7. Qe3 Kf1 8. Qf3+ Ke1 9. Kf6 Kd2 10. Qf2 Kd1 11. Qd4+ Kc1 12. Qe3+ Kd1 13. Qd3+ Ke1 14. Kf5 Kf2 15. Qd2 Kf1 16. Qf4+ Ke1 17. Ke4 Kd1 18. Qf3 (18. Qd6+ { is another possible win of many, e.g. } 18... Kc1 19. Qb4 Kd1 20. Qb1+ Kd2 21. Qd3+ Kc1 (21... Ke1 22. Kf3 { transposes to the game }) 22. Qxe2 $18) 18... Kd2 19. Qd3+ Ke1 20. Kf3 Kf1 21. Qxe2+ Kg1 22. Qg2# *


