[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/TonyRo"]
[FEN "7K/8/8/3Q4/8/8/pk6/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.01.17"]
[UTCTime "00:27:28"]

{ As is common in endings, the rook pawn is an annoying exception. We've already seen that this is an easy win with a b,d,e, or g-pawn, but here (along with bishop pawns) is a draw due to a cute stalemate motif, for instance: }
1. Qb5+ (1. Qd4+ Kb1 2. Qb4+ Ka1! { illustrates the same idea. }) 1... Ka1! $10 { Already we see the issue - when Black's king blocks the a-pawn, White can't move advance his king, as it would immediately result in a stalemate. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 2. Qa4 Kb1 3. Qb3+ Ka1! { and so on - White can't make progress. } 4. Qa3 *


[Event "Queen vs. Rook or Bishop Pawns: BP - Distant King"]
[Date "2018.01.17"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Queen vs. Rook or Bishop Pawns"]
[ChapterName "BP - Distant King"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kkoVo7Fy/rSa8G4GG"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/TonyRo"]
[FEN "7K/8/4Q3/8/8/8/2p5/1k6 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.01.17"]
[UTCTime "00:33:50"]

{ This is the other exception. With White's king unable to participate, there's a second stalemate motif that saves Black in the event of a bishop's pawn. }
1. Qb3+ Ka1! { And already we see the point - Qxc2 stalemates again. Any check will force ...Kb1 and we'd be back to essentially the initial position, and any king move allows promotion. } { [%cal Gb3c2] } (1... Kc1 { also draws, but just wastes time using the same motif as in the main line, e.g. } 2. Kg7 Kd2 3. Qb4+ Kd1 4. Qd4+ Kc1 5. Qc3 Kb1 6. Qb3+ Ka1!) 2. Qxc2 $10 { And stalemate. } *


