[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/TonyRo"]
[FEN "8/8/3Q4/1K6/8/8/1kp5/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2018.03.21"]
[UTCTime "01:35:24"]

{ This is a useful trick to know, in case your king is just outside the short-side winning zone. The idea is that luring the Black king to b2 and placing your queen on e2 (this is important - the same idea with Qd2 fails because a promotion would threaten the White king and not give him time for a king move) transposes back to positions discussed previously. A good rule of thumb for the defender of the short side is to always choose the a1-square! } { [%csl Ga4,Gb4,Gc4,Gc3,Gd3,Ge3,Ge2,Ge1,Yb3,Yd2] }
1. Qb4+ Ka2 2. Qc3 Kb1 3. Qb3+ Ka1 $7 (3... Kc1?? 4. Kc4 Kd2 { [%csl Ga5,Gb5,Gc5,Gd5,Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gg4,Gg3,Gg2,Gg1] } (4... Kd1 5. Kd3 $18 { [%cal Gb3d1] }) 5. Qd3+ Kc1 6. Kb3 $18) 4. Qc3+ Kb1 $7 5. Qd3 Kb2 (5... Kc1?? 6. Kb4 Kb2 7. Qd2 Kb1 8. Kb3 $18) (5... Ka1 $10) 6. Qe2!? (6. Qd2 Kb1 7. Kb4 c1=Q $10 { [%cal Rc1d2,Rb4b3] }) 6... Kb1?? (6... Ka1! 7. Kb4 c1=Q 8. Kb3 Qb1+ $10) 7. Kb4 c1=Q 8. Kb3 $18 *


